For an upload that is only successful once all chunks have reached edge, create the file with an edge write tier and then create the parent row at the same tier:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label: "Profile photo",
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

When downloading, treat incomplete local data as a separate state from a missing file. Read with `tier: "edge"` if the product requires a complete edge snapshot, and handle the two errors differently:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return { kind: "ready", blob };
} catch (error) {
  if (error.name === "FileNotFoundError") {
    return { kind: "missing" };
  }
  if (error.name === "IncompleteFileDataError") {
    return { kind: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  }
  throw error;
}
```

`IncompleteFileDataError` means the file row is visible but one or more chunks are absent or wrong-sized locally or upstream; surface that as a recoverable incomplete-download state rather than pretending the file does not exist.

Delete in dependency order while inherited permissions still exist: load the parent upload first, load its file through the current reference, delete every part row, then delete the file row, and only then delete the parent upload.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the parent first. If you do, the inherited delete grants for `files` and `file_parts` can disappear before cleanup runs, leaving orphaned chunks behind.

Create a small application boundary around the dynamic Rust row API rather than decoding `Vec<Value>` ad hoc in handlers.

- Define each query projection once with a matching Rust struct, for example `TodoRow { id, title, done, description }`.
- Keep the `QueryBuilder` select order and the decoder together. `JazzClient::query(...)` returns `Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)>`, so write a fallible decoder like `fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError>`.
- Validate exact column count, `Value` variant, and nullability on every field. Reject schema drift instead of coercing it.
- Build schemas with `SchemaBuilder` and `TableSchema::builder`, and writes with public APIs plus `row_input!` for inserts.
- Centralise write helpers as well: small functions for `insert`, `update`, `delete`, and optional `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer|GlobalServer)` when the caller needs settled state.
- Reuse one long-lived `JazzClient` per process, then pass around scoped clones or `for_session(...)` clients rather than reconnecting.

Minimal pattern:
```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 3 { return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch); }

    let title = match &values[0] {
        Value::Text(v) => v.clone(),
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch),
    };
    let done = match values[1] {
        Value::Boolean(v) => v,
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch),
    };
    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::Null => None,
        Value::Text(v) => Some(v.clone()),
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch),
    };

    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```
That gives you a typed application layer without pretending the Rust crate has generated typed table handles.

Use one process-wide connected `JazzClient` with backend transport credentials, then scope each request to the authenticated caller via `for_session(session)`.

Endpoint design:
- Verify the bearer token or session cookie with the installed public auth API.
- Map the stable subject to a Jazz `Session`.
- Create `let db = app_client.for_session(session);`.
- Read the target row through `db`, not the backend client, so row visibility matches the caller.
- Apply the update through `db` so authorship and policy evaluation use the same caller identity.
- Await `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer)` or `GlobalServer` inside `tokio::time::timeout(...)`.
- Requery through `db` after settlement before returning if the contract requires a server-visible representation.
- Map auth failure to `401`, filtered/missing row to `404`, policy rejection to `403` or domain conflict, timeout to `503/504`, and decoder mismatch to internal error.

Sketch:
```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    AuthenticatedUser(user): AuthenticatedUser,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(body): Json<UpdateTodoBody>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, AppError> {
    let session = Session::from_subject(user.subject);
    let db = state.client.for_session(session);

    let batch_id = db.update(id, vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(body.done))])?;

    tokio::time::timeout(
        Duration::from_secs(5),
        db.wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer),
    )
    .await
    .map_err(|_| AppError::Timeout)??;

    let rows = db.query(todo_by_id_query(id)).await?;
    let row = rows.into_iter().next().ok_or(AppError::NotFound)?;
    Ok(Json(decode_todo(row.0, &row.1)?))
}
```
Key boundary: backend credential authorises the service transport role; the scoped session determines row policy and updater identity.

Write it as a black-box integration test using the real router plus independent clients and a real `JazzServer` when you need permissions, authorship, and cross-client visibility.

Topology:
- Start a test JWT issuer and a `JazzServer` with the production schema and row policies.
- Connect one long-lived service client using the backend credential.
- Start the production Axum router on an ephemeral listener or exercise it through Tower.
- Connect independent user clients for seeding and verification.
- Seed a row as user A and await `EdgeServer`.
- Call the real authenticated endpoint as user B.
- Await settlement, then query from an independent verifier client and decode the row plus provenance columns if selected.
- Assert the updated value is visible server-side, creator is still user A, updater is user B.
- Call the same route as denied user C and assert `404` for filtered absence or `403` for explicit rejection, depending on policy design.
- Shut down clients, listener, issuer, server, and any subscription streams the public API lets you own.

Test shape:
```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn update_route_preserves_authorship_and_permissions() {
    // 1. issuer + JazzServer + production router
    // 2. user A seeds row, wait_for_batch(..., EdgeServer)
    // 3. user B calls real HTTP route with valid token
    // 4. independent client queries authoritative result
    // 5. assert value changed, creator unchanged, updater == user B
    // 6. user C call is denied/filtered
}
```
Use public builders, `row_input!`, bounded waits such as `wait_for_query` or `wait_for_batch`, and avoid fixed sleeps or copied route logic inside the test.
